From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] sky2: enable Baikal IRQ block + trust Orbis PHY state

v78 wired up the SMI MDIO accessor and got sky2 to bind cleanly on
Baikal (no more phy I/O errors, enp0s20f1 netdev created).  But link
stayed DOWN and SMI eventually went stuck — same symptom as the v77/v77b
standalone driver.

Root cause confirmed via Orbis RE: Baikal's MAC has its own IRQ block
that has to be enabled for the MAC clocks (and the SMI controller they
feed) to stay alive.  Orbis's mts_intr enables it on the first interrupt:
   BAR+0x204 = 0x10001388  (full IRQ enable)
   BAR+0x54  = 0x7bfffe    (per-IRQ mask)
Without these writes the MAC idles out after ~1min, the SMI register
starts echoing the last command back instead of actually clocking the
PHY, and the link transition events never reach sky2's ISR.

This patch:
  1. Adds sky2_baikal_irq_enable() and calls it from sky2_probe right
     after sky2_reset().
  2. Drops the BMCR soft-reset + AN restart we did on Baikal in v78.
     Every write to BMCR appears to de-stabilise the MT7531 PHY's
     handshake with the MAC; v79 trusts Orbis's pre-handoff PHY state
     entirely (the PHY had already auto-negotiated under Orbis and
     reached link-up — its SBL setup is intact across the hand-off).

Pass criterion: enp0s20f1 should reach `Link UP at 1000Mbps full
duplex` and pinging 192.168.50.95 from the Linux side should reply.
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/marvell/sky2.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/marvell/sky2.c
@@ -202,8 +202,23 @@
 	} while (--timeout);
 	return -ETIMEDOUT;
 }
+
+/*
+ * The Baikal MAC's SMI block stays alive only while the MAC's main IRQ
+ * block is active.  Orbis's mts_intr enables this on the first interrupt:
+ *   BAR+0x204 = 0x10001388  (full IRQ enable)
+ *   BAR+0x54  = 0x7bfffe    (per-IRQ mask)
+ * Without these writes, v77/v78 saw SMI controller idle out after ~1min
+ * and the PHY lose its register interface entirely.
+ */
+static void sky2_baikal_irq_enable(struct sky2_hw *hw)
+{
+	sky2_write32(hw, 0x204, 0x10001388);
+	sky2_write32(hw, 0x054, 0x007bfffe);
+}
 #else
 static inline bool sky2_is_baikal(const struct sky2_hw *hw) { return false; }
+static inline void sky2_baikal_irq_enable(struct sky2_hw *hw) {}
 #endif

 /* Access to PHY via serial interconnect */
@@ -399,22 +414,12 @@

 #ifdef CONFIG_X86_PS4
 	if (sky2_is_baikal(hw)) {
-		/* MT7531 (or older Marvell 88E6XXX) has its own setup driven by
-		 * Orbis SBL.  Skip all Yukon-PHY-specific writes; they target
-		 * Marvell vendor pages that don't exist here.  Just soft-reset
-		 * BMCR and restart auto-negotiation. */
-		int i;
-		u16 v;
-
-		gm_phy_write(hw, port, PHY_MARV_CTRL, PHY_CT_RESET);
-		for (i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
-			v = gm_phy_read(hw, port, PHY_MARV_CTRL);
-			if (!(v & PHY_CT_RESET))
-				break;
-			usleep_range(1000, 2000);
-		}
-		gm_phy_write(hw, port, PHY_MARV_CTRL,
-			     PHY_CT_ANE | PHY_CT_RE_CFG);
+		/* Trust Orbis SBL's PHY state — every write we do to BMCR
+		 * de-stabilises the MT7531 link.  v78 wrote BMCR reset + AN
+		 * restart and got the SMI controller into a stuck state with
+		 * link DOWN.  v79: leave PHY entirely alone.  The Baikal IRQ
+		 * block enable (in sky2_reset's Baikal branch) is what keeps
+		 * the MAC clocks alive going forward. */
 		return;
 	}
 #endif
@@ -5126,6 +5131,9 @@

 	sky2_reset(hw);

+	if (sky2_is_baikal(hw))
+		sky2_baikal_irq_enable(hw);
+
 	dev = sky2_init_netdev(hw, 0, using_dac, wol_default);
 	if (!dev) {
 		err = -ENOMEM;
